  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Historically, laws against money laundering emerged to combat organized crime\n- Initial focus was on hiding proceeds from illegal activities like drug trafficking\n\n2. United States Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Expanded criminal penalties\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Made money laundering a federal crime\n\n3. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- International conventions like UN Vienna Convention (1988) and Palermo Convention (2000)\n- Gradually developed global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing prevention\n- Enhanced reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n5. Modern Era\n- Continuing evolution of regulations\n- Increased digital/cryptocurrency compliance requirements\n- Growing international cooperation in enforcement\n\nThe legal framework continues to develop in response to changing financial technologies and criminal methods.",
